Pearson-Lee height data

These heights are roughly \(\, N(68.68, 2.81) \,\), so

  • our best guess of a height is the average, 68.68 inches,
  • which will likely be wrong,
  • but probably not by more than 2 SDs, 5.63 inches.
  • This is a null model. Are more informed guesses better?

Pearson-Lee height data

The average height of a group of sons depends linearly on the fathers given height.

  • Using this data, \[\text{Average height of sons} = 33.89 + .514 \times \text{Father's height} \, ,\] \[\text{i.e.}, \quad \quad E( y \mid x ) = 33.89 + .514 \, x \ .\]
  • This is simple linear regression, handled by lm in R :

Pearson-Lee height data

This dataset illustrates regression and the regression effect nicely, but things are actually too nice in this example!

  • Both variables are roughly normally distributed, which is not necessary at all.
  • Many interesting datasets are too small to organize into groups, compute group means, and observe the linear relationship so easily.

UNICEF data

  • Literacy rates

The simple linear regression model

We use this model when we believe that \[y ~ = ~ \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} x + \epsilon \ . \]

  • Main assumptions: the random error \(\epsilon\) has constant variance and mean zero and is uncorrelated across observations.
  • Consequences: \[ E(y \mid x) = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x \ , \ \operatorname{Var}(y \mid x) = \sigma^2\]
  • Another assumption: values of the predictor are known exactly.

The simple linear regression model

  • This model only makes sense if the mean response is a reasonable summary of \(y\). Not true for categorical responses!
  • Neither the parameters nor the error can ever be known; they can only be estimated from observations.
  • Nothing is assumed to be normally distributed
  • yet inferences and model assessment are still possible!

Ordinary least squares

This is the standard method for estimating \(\, \beta_{0} \,\) and \(\, \beta_{1} \,\).

  • Candidate predictive model: \(\quad \hat{y} ~ = ~ a + bx\)
  • Minimize the sum of squared residuals, \[\text{RSS} ~ = ~ \sum{ \left( y - \hat{y} \right)^2 } ~ = ~ \sum{ \left( y - a - bx \right)^2 }\]
  • Calculus: \[\frac{\partial}{\partial a} \left( \text{RSS} \right) ~ = ~ 0 \quad \Longrightarrow \quad \hat{\beta}_{0} ~ = ~ \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_{1} \, \bar{x}\] \[\frac{\partial}{\partial b} \left( \text{RSS} \right) ~ = ~ 0 \quad \Longrightarrow \quad \hat{\beta}_{1} ~ = ~ r \left( \frac{ s_{y} }{ s_{x} } \right)\]

The Gauss-Markov theorem

OLS is BLUE :

  • These formulas are the Best Linear Unbiased Estimates: \[E( \hat{\beta}_{0} ) = \beta_{0} \ , \quad E( \hat{\beta}_{1} ) = \beta_{1} \ , \quad \text{minimal variance} \ .\]
  • Only the previous assumptions are needed; no normality!
  • This result relies on knowing the predictors values exactly.

The Gauss-Markov theorem

The mean standard error, \[\text{MSE} ~ = ~ \frac{ \text{RSS} }{ n-2 } ~ = ~ \frac{ \sum{ \left( y - \hat{y} \right)^2 } }{ n-2 } \ , \] is an unbiased estimate of \(\, \sigma^2 ~ = ~ \operatorname{Var}( \epsilon ) \,\).

  • The residual standard error, \(\, \text{RSE} ~ = ~ \sqrt{\text{MSE}} \,\), is more practical; describes variability and compares models.
  • Heights: RSE = 2.437 inches versus SD(\(\, y \,\)) = 2.81 inches
  • UNICEF: RSE = 23.07 deaths versus SD(\(\, y \,\)) = 28.49 deaths

Chebyshevs inequality

  • If \(\, Y \,\) is a random variable with mean \(\, \mu \,\) and SD \(\, \sigma \,\), then \[ \operatorname{Pr}\left\{ \ | Y - \mu | > k \sigma \ \right\} ~ \leq ~ \frac{1}{k^2} \ .\]
  • True regardless of distribution!
  • If the regression model is correct, then at least 75% of responses will be within 2 RSEs of the regression line.

Chebyshevs inequality

Follows from Markovs inequality, \[ \text{Markov!} \]

The coefficient of determination

This descriptive statistic compares the regression model and the null model.

  • \(\text{OLS} \ \Longrightarrow \ \sum{ \left( y - \bar{y} \right)^2 } ~ = ~ \sum{ \left( y - \hat{y} \right)^2 } + \sum{ \left( \hat{y} - \bar{y} \right)^2 } \ .\)
  • Using the predictor reduces variability: \[\sum{ \left( \hat{y} - \bar{y} \right)^2 } ~ = ~ \sum{ \left( y - \bar{y} \right)^2 } - \sum{ \left( y - \hat{y} \right)^2 }\]
  • Percentage reduction: \[R^2 ~ = ~ \frac{ \sum{ \left( \hat{y} - \bar{y} \right)^2 } }{ \sum{ \left( y - \bar{y} \right)^2 } } ~ = ~ 1 - \frac{ \sum{ \left( y - \hat{y} \right)^2 } }{\sum{ \left( y - \bar{y} \right)^2 }} \ .\]

The coefficient of determination

\(R^2\) is the relative reduction in variability gained by using the predictor instead of ignoring it. Nothing more, nothing less!

  • Beware: A true model can have a low \(R^2\); an irrelevant model can have a large \(R^2\).
  • It does not “explain the variation” in \(\, y \,\)!
  • It can only increase when adding predictors adjusting \(R^2\) doesnt really help.
  • Use with care and look at your data!

The normal regression model

Finally, consider adding the assumption that \[\epsilon ~ \sim ~ N(0, \sigma^2) \ .\]

  • Yields formulas for sampling distributions:
  • Enables inferences and hypothesis tests:

Summary

  • Even simple linear regression is not so simple!
  • Pay more attention to the RSE, less to \(R^2\).
  • Stop spreading the rumor that normality is required for linear regression.
  • Be sure to understand all those \(t\)-scores and \(p\)-values before (mis)using them.
  • Dont use linear regression to model categorical responses.
